         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1988">
               <p>While a servant in the household of Lady <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0964.xml"/>Huntingdon</persName>, Taylor underwent a
                  spiritual awakening in the mid-<date>1730s</date>. With their encouragement he was
                  soon preaching and gathering societies in the <placeName>Sheffield</placeName>
                  area, in some association with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1121.xml"
                     />Benjamin Ingham</persName>. Taylor was instrumental in the conversion of
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0143.xml"/>John Bennet</persName> in
                     <date when="1742">1742</date>. While ever an <seg ana="itinerancy"
                     >itinerant</seg>, Taylor was independent of mind and fluctuated in his
                  alliances, between Methodists, Moravians, and even Quakers for a while. See
                  Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 412–13; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>,
                  1082–83; Pawson, <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi>, 3:142; and Vickers, <hi
                     rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 345.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
